Project Summary -

The given data shows various attributes of applications available on the playstore. The dataset contains 10841 rows and 13 columns. Below are 3 types of data manipulation - data collection, data cleaning and exploratory data analysis.

This project explores Google Play Store data to uncover key insights into app performance, user behavior, and monetization strategies. The analysis focused on installs, reviews, ratings, pricing, categories, and app sizes to identify drivers of growth and business opportunities.

Data collection entails finding columns through python commands which are head(), tail(), describe(), info(), row() and column(). Duplicated columns have been found and deleted including many other forms of data organization.

Data cleaning entails deleting duplicated columns found in the dataset which were around 1400. We also removed characters like +, -, $, et cetera.

Prior to data visualization we begin data wrangling, null values are detected and replaced with the command fillna() or dropped using drop().

Exploratory data analysis entails making various charts to depict relationship between variables. Utilized charts include but not limited to bar graph, pie chart, heat map, et cetera. These charts give various inference like top 5 installed categories, top 5 highest reviewed categories, et cetera.

Findings reveal that 92% of apps are free, making them the most effective channel for mass adoption and review generation. Popular categories such as Games, Family, and Tools dominate installs, while niche segments like Teen and Mature 17+ provide opportunities for loyalty and premium pricing. Everyone rated apps represent the largest market share, making them ideal for scale and visibility, whereas age-specific apps help target premium users.

64% of reviews are positive, reflecting overall user satisfaction. Categories like Games, Social, and Productivity deliver both high installs and strong ratings, positioning them as safe investments. Pricing analysis showed that while free apps capture scale, premium apps with high installs drive the most revenue, though raising prices too aggressively risks losing users.

Finally, variable app sizes dominate the market, with lightweight apps serving storage-limited users and larger apps appealing to premium audiences. Businesses can maximize growth by balancing free and premium offerings across diverse categories, ensuring both reach and loyalty.

Variables Description

Dataset 1
App- contains app name and sometimes a short descption
Category- shows which category the app belongs to out of 33 possible categories
Rating- average rating of app given by users out of 5 stars
Reviews- number of reviews given by users
Size- disc space required for installing app
Installs- approximate number of app intallation
Type- shows whether app is free or paid
Price- price of paid app
Content Rating- shows users of which age are suitable for the app content
Genres- shows genre of app
Last Updated- shows when app was last updated
Current Ver- shows current version of app
Android Ver- shows android version of app

Dataset 2
App- contains app name and sometimes a short descption
Translated Review- shows review of app by user translated in english
Sentiment- shows feeling of user towards app among 'Positive','Negative'or 'Neutral'
Sentiment Polarity- shows magnitude of sentiment towards app from 1 to -1, 1 meaning positive and -1 meaning negative
Sentiment Subjectivity- shows how close the review is to the general review

Chart - 1

In[]:
# Chart - 1 , finding out how many apps are paid and free

plt.figure(figsize=(7,7))
plt.title('Distribution of Free vs Paid Apps', fontsize=18, fontweight='bold')

# Get values
counts = price_df.Type.value_counts()[:2]
num_types = len(counts)

# Pie chart
wedges, texts, autotexts = plt.pie(
    counts,
    labels=counts.index,
    autopct='%1.1f%%',
    startangle=90,
    explode=[0.05]*num_types,
    colors=['#66c2a5','#fc8d62'],
    wedgeprops={'edgecolor':'white'},
    textprops={'fontsize':12}
)

# Center circle for donut look
centre_circle = plt.Circle((0,0),0.70,fc='white')
fig = plt.gcf()
fig.gca().add_artist(centre_circle)

# Bolden percentage text
for autotext in autotexts:
    autotext.set_fontsize(12)
    autotext.set_weight('bold')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
1. Why did you pick the specific chart?

the pie chart masterfully depicts the percentage difference between paid and unpaid apps

2. What is/are the insight(s) found from the chart?

7.4% of all apps are paid

3. Will the gained insights help creating a positive business impact?

Are there any insights that lead to negative growth? Justify with specific reason.

Negative growth could come from heavily investing in paid a apps since 92% of the market is free apps.

# Chart - 2

# Count categories
top_categories = play_store['Category'].value_counts().head(10)

# Plot bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
top_categories.plot(kind='bar', color='skyblue', edgecolor='black')

plt.title("Top 10 Most Frequent App Categories", fontsize=18, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel("Category", fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel("Number of Apps", fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.show()
1. Why did you pick the specific chart?

Top 10 Most Frequent App Categories chart was chosen because it clearly shows the supply side of the Play Store which categories developers are investing in the most. This provides a snapshot of market competition and app density.

2. What is/are the insight(s) found from the chart?

Family apps dominate the market with the highest number of apps, reflecting developers strong focus on family-friendly and kids-oriented solutions.

Games are the second-most frequent category, showing how competitive and crowded the gaming segment is.

Tools, Medical, and Business apps follow, highlighting demand for utility and professional use cases.

Categories like Lifestyle, Sports, and Personalization have relatively fewer apps, which may indicate either lower demand or less developer focus.

High app frequency does not always mean high installs (e.g., Family has many apps, but installs may be fragmented among them).

3. Will the gained insights help creating a positive business impact?

Are there any insights that lead to negative growth? Justify with specific reason.

Positive Business Impact

This insight helps businesses identify competitive markets (e.g., Games, Family) versus underserved niches (e.g., Lifestyle, Sports).

Developers can differentiate in overcrowded markets or target less-saturated categories to improve visibility and installs.

Businesses entering Tools, Productivity, or Business apps can expect stable long-term engagement since these are necessity-driven.

Negative Growth Risks

Overcrowding in Family and Games means new apps face high competition, low visibility, and possible user fatigue.

High frequency profitability; too many similar apps may lead to price wars or low user retention.

Investing heavily in already saturated categories without innovation may result in negative ROI.

# Chart - 3

# Count sentiment values
sentiment_counts = user_reviews['Sentiment'].value_counts()

plt.figure(figsize=(7,7))
plt.pie(
    sentiment_counts,
    labels=sentiment_counts.index,
    autopct='%1.1f%%',
    startangle=140,
    colors=['skyblue', 'lightgreen', 'salmon'],
    wedgeprops={'edgecolor': 'black'}
)

plt.title("Sentiment Distribution of User Reviews", fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.show()
1. Why did you pick the specific chart?

This chart was chosen because user reviews and feedback directly reflect customer satisfaction and product quality, which are essential for business growth. Unlike installs, which show reach, reviews capture user experience, providing insights into retention, loyalty, and brand trust.

2. What is/are the insight(s) found from the chart?

Positive sentiment dominates (64.1%) Most users are satisfied with their app experiences. This shows that market practices (pricing, usability, features) are working well overall.

22.1% Negative reviews Nearly 1 in 5 users are unhappy, highlighting areas for improvement such as app crashes, excessive ads, or poor updates.

13.8% Neutral reviews These are undecided users who could be converted into promoters with better engagement, feature enhancements, or loyalty strategies.

Balance of sentiment While positives outweigh negatives, the combined Neutral + Negative (35.9%) cannot be ignored this is a significant portion of the user base.

3. Will the gained insights help creating a positive business impact?

Are there any insights that lead to negative growth? Justify with specific reason.

Positive Business Impact

Companies can leverage the strong majority of positive reviews (64%) for marketing, testimonials, and building brand credibility.

A majority happy user base indicates a strong foundation to scale apps, retain users, and introduce premium features.

Neutral users are opportunities By improving customer support, app performance, and communication, businesses can shift them toward positive engagement.

Negative Growth Risks

22% negative reviews is substantial If unresolved, these dissatisfied users may churn, discourage new downloads, and lower app store rankings.

Negative reviews spread faster One poor experience often influences many potential users, harming growth.

If businesses ignore neutral/negative segments, the gap between installs and retention will widen, resulting in short-term growth but long-term stagnation.

# Chart - 4

# Ensure numeric types
play_store['Reviews'] = pd.to_numeric(play_store['Reviews'], errors='coerce')
play_store['Installed'] = pd.to_numeric(play_store['Installed'], errors='coerce')

# Drop NA values
subset = play_store[['Reviews', 'Installed']].dropna()

In[]:
import scipy.stats as stats

# Clean Priced (remove extreme outliers, e.g., > $400 unrealistic on Play Store)
price_filtered = play_store[(play_store["Priced"] >= 0) & (play_store["Priced"] <= 400)]

# Log-transform to handle skewness
price_filtered["log_Priced"] = np.log1p(price_filtered["Priced"])
price_filtered["log_Installed"] = np.log1p(price_filtered["Installed"])

pearson_corr, p_pearson = stats.pearsonr(price_filtered["log_Priced"], price_filtered["log_Installed"])
spearman_corr, p_spearman = stats.spearmanr(price_filtered["log_Priced"], price_filtered["log_Installed"])

print("Pearson correlation:", pearson_corr, "p-value:", p_pearson)
print("Spearman correlation:", spearman_corr, "p-value:", p_spearman)


free_installs = price_filtered[price_filtered["Priced"] == 0]["Installed"]
paid_installs = price_filtered[price_filtered["Priced"] > 0]["Installed"]

# Mann-Whitney U test (non-parametric since data is skewed)
stat, p_value = stats.mannwhitneyu(free_installs, paid_installs, alternative="two-sided")

print("Mann-Whitney U test p-value:", p_value)

# Chart - 12 visualization code

# Ensure Priced is numeric
play_store['Priced'] = play_store['Priced'].replace('[\$,]', '', regex=True).astype(float)

# Drop rows with missing Rating
subset = play_store[['Priced', 'Installed', 'Rating']].dropna()

# Bin Installed and Priced into ranges
subset['Price_bin'] = pd.qcut(subset['Priced'], q=10, duplicates='drop')      # 10 quantile bins
subset['Install_bin'] = pd.qcut(subset['Installed'], q=10, duplicates='drop') # 10 quantile bins

# Pivot table: average rating in each bin
pivot = subset.pivot_table(
    values='Rating',
    index='Install_bin',
    columns='Price_bin',
    aggfunc='mean'
)

# Plot heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
sns.heatmap(pivot, annot=False, cmap="viridis", cbar_kws={'label': 'Average Rating'})

# Chart - 13 visualization code
# Group by Category: compute total Installed and average Rating
top5 = (play_store.groupby("Category")
          .agg(Installed=('Installed', 'sum'),
               avg_rating=('Rating', 'mean'))
          .reset_index()
          .sort_values(by="Installed", ascending=False)
          .head(5))

# Bubble chart
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
plt.scatter(top5['Category'], top5['avg_rating'],
            s=top5['Installed'] / 1e6,   # scale bubble size
            alpha=0.6, edgecolors='k', color="skyblue")

# Add text labels inside bubbles
for i, row in top5.iterrows():
    plt.text(row['Category'], row['avg_rating'],
             f"{row['Installed']//1_000_000}M",
             ha='center', va='center', fontsize=9, weight='bold')

plt.ylabel("Average Rating")
plt.xlabel("Category")
plt.title("Top 5 Categories by Installed (Bubble Size ~ Installed)")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()
